        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Decomposing Token Cost Into Its Drivers"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A GenAI cost forecast that treats total spend as a single number cannot tell you which lever to pull when the forecast is wrong. Scenario planning requires decomposing total cost into its constituent drivers, assigning a range to each, and computing the resulting cost distribution. The six primary drivers are: request volume, tokens per request, cache hit rate, model tier, provider pricing, and batch versus real-time split. Each driver is independently controllable and has a different uncertainty range."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Scenario Planning for Token Cost Drivers",
          "title": null
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Six Cost Drivers in Detail"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Driver 1: Request Volume"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Request volume is the product of monthly active users (MAU), sessions per user per month, and requests per session. In growth phase this is the dominant driver. A 2\u00d7 increase in MAU \u2014 typical for a successful feature in its first year \u2014 directly doubles token spend if all other drivers are held constant."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass RequestVolumeScenario:\n    mau:               int     # monthly active users\n    sessions_per_user: float   # average sessions per user per month\n    requests_per_session: float  # average LLM calls per session\n\n    @property\n    def monthly_requests(self) -> float:\n        return self.mau * self.sessions_per_user * self.requests_per_session\n\n# Bear / Base / Bull for a CX assistant feature\nbear = RequestVolumeScenario(mau=5_000,  sessions_per_user=3.0, requests_per_session=2.5)\nbase = RequestVolumeScenario(mau=12_000, sessions_per_user=4.2, requests_per_session=3.1)\nbull = RequestVolumeScenario(mau=25_000, sessions_per_user=5.5, requests_per_session=4.0)\n# bear: 37,500/mo  base: 156,240/mo  bull: 550,000/mo"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Driver 2: Tokens per Request"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tokens per request has three sub-components: system prompt length (fixed), user-provided context (variable), and completion length (controlled by `max_tokens` and the model's natural stop). A RAG feature that injects five retrieved document chunks at 800 tokens each will consume 4 000 tokens of context before the user's question is even appended. Prompt engineering and context compression are the primary levers for this driver."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@dataclass\nclass TokensPerRequestScenario:\n    system_prompt_tokens:  int   # fixed per request type\n    avg_context_tokens:    int   # injected documents, history, etc.\n    avg_user_tokens:       int   # user message\n    avg_completion_tokens: int   # model output\n\n    @property\n    def total_input_tokens(self) -> int:\n        return (self.system_prompt_tokens +\n                self.avg_context_tokens +\n                self.avg_user_tokens)\n\n    @property\n    def total_tokens(self) -> int:\n        return self.total_input_tokens + self.avg_completion_tokens\n\n# Bear = optimised prompts; Base = current; Bull = feature expansion adds more context\nbear = TokensPerRequestScenario(500, 1_200, 80, 250)   # 2,030 total\nbase = TokensPerRequestScenario(800, 2_400, 110, 380)  # 3,690 total\nbull = TokensPerRequestScenario(800, 4_800, 130, 500)  # 6,230 total"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Driver 3: Cache Hit Rate"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prompt caching reduces the effective input token cost for repeated or partially repeated prompts. OpenAI and Anthropic both offer caching at 50\u201390% of the standard input price for cached tokens. A feature with a large shared system prompt (e.g. a 2 000-token instruction block) that is reused across most calls can achieve 40\u201360% cache hit rates, materially reducing cost."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@dataclass\nclass CacheScenario:\n    cache_hit_rate:       float  # 0.0\u20131.0\n    cached_token_discount: float  # e.g. 0.50 = cached tokens cost 50% of normal\n\n    def effective_input_cost_multiplier(self) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Fraction of full input price paid after accounting for caching.\"\"\"\n        return (1 - self.cache_hit_rate) + self.cache_hit_rate * (1 - self.cached_token_discount)\n\nbear = CacheScenario(cache_hit_rate=0.60, cached_token_discount=0.50)  # 0.70\u00d7 cost\nbase = CacheScenario(cache_hit_rate=0.30, cached_token_discount=0.50)  # 0.85\u00d7 cost\nbull = CacheScenario(cache_hit_rate=0.05, cached_token_discount=0.50)  # 0.975\u00d7 cost\n# Bear case: heavy caching investment reduces effective input cost by 30%"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Driver 4: Model Tier"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Model tier is the highest-leverage single decision in GenAI cost management. The price difference between the largest and smallest models from the same provider is often 10\u201320\u00d7. A feature that runs on GPT-4o for every request when GPT-4o-mini would suffice for 80% of them is paying a 5\u20138\u00d7 premium on that 80%."
          }
        ]
      },
