      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "@dataclass\nclass ModelMixScenario:\n    # Fraction of requests routed to each tier\n    frontier_fraction:  float  # e.g. gpt-4o\n    standard_fraction:  float  # e.g. gpt-4o-mini\n    embed_fraction:     float  # embedding-only calls\n\n    # Per-request cost for each tier (USD)\n    frontier_cost_per_req:  float\n    standard_cost_per_req:  float\n    embed_cost_per_req:     float\n\n    def blended_cost_per_request(self) -> float:\n        return (\n            self.frontier_fraction * self.frontier_cost_per_req +\n            self.standard_fraction * self.standard_cost_per_req +\n            self.embed_fraction    * self.embed_cost_per_req\n        )\n\n# Bear: intelligent routing sends 80% to mini\nbear = ModelMixScenario(0.20, 0.70, 0.10, 0.0369, 0.00222, 0.000156)\n# Base: default to frontier for all chat calls\nbase = ModelMixScenario(0.80, 0.10, 0.10, 0.0369, 0.00222, 0.000156)\n# Bull: new features require frontier exclusively\nbull = ModelMixScenario(0.95, 0.00, 0.05, 0.0369, 0.00222, 0.000156)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Driver 5: Provider Pricing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Provider pricing has historically trended downward \u2014 GPT-4-level capability costs roughly 20\u00d7 less today than it did two years ago. However, forecasting continued price decreases is risky: provider pricing is a commercial decision, not a law of physics. Model the base case as flat pricing, the bear case as a 20% price decrease (optimisation headroom), and the bull case as a 15% increase (new premium model replaces current tier)."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Driver 6: Batch vs Real-Time Split"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Workloads that do not require sub-second latency \u2014 document processing, overnight analysis, bulk data enrichment \u2014 can be routed to the provider's batch API, which typically offers a 50% discount. The opportunity is significant: batch-eligible workloads in a mixed platform can represent 30\u201360% of total token volume. The cost of the batch split is latency \u2014 batch jobs complete within 24 hours rather than milliseconds."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Building a Scenario Model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The scenario model combines all six drivers into an annual cost estimate for each combination of bear / base / bull values. Rather than running all possible combinations (2^6 = 64 scenarios), use the standard three-scenario approach: bear sets all drivers to their optimistic values simultaneously, base uses expected values, and bull uses pessimistic values."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\n\n@dataclass\nclass AnnualCostScenario:\n    scenario_name:         str\n    monthly_requests:      float\n    total_tokens_per_req:  float\n    cache_multiplier:      float    # effective input cost fraction\n    blended_cost_per_req:  float    # USD after model mix\n    batch_fraction:        float\n    batch_discount:        float\n    provider_price_factor: float    # 1.0 = flat, 0.8 = 20% decrease\n\n    @property\n    def monthly_cost_usd(self) -> float:\n        # Adjust for batch discount and provider price change\n        adjusted_cost = (\n            self.blended_cost_per_req\n            * self.cache_multiplier\n            * self.provider_price_factor\n            * (1 - self.batch_fraction * self.batch_discount)\n        )\n        return self.monthly_requests * adjusted_cost\n\n    @property\n    def annual_cost_usd(self) -> float:\n        return self.monthly_cost_usd * 12\n\nbear_scenario = AnnualCostScenario(\n    scenario_name         = \"Bear\",\n    monthly_requests      = 37_500,\n    total_tokens_per_req  = 2030,\n    cache_multiplier      = 0.70,\n    blended_cost_per_req  = 0.0045,\n    batch_fraction        = 0.50,\n    batch_discount        = 0.50,\n    provider_price_factor = 0.80,\n)\n\nbase_scenario = AnnualCostScenario(\n    scenario_name         = \"Base\",\n    monthly_requests      = 156_240,\n    total_tokens_per_req  = 3690,\n    cache_multiplier      = 0.85,\n    blended_cost_per_req  = 0.0310,\n    batch_fraction        = 0.20,\n    batch_discount        = 0.50,\n    provider_price_factor = 1.00,\n)\n\nbull_scenario = AnnualCostScenario(\n    scenario_name         = \"Bull\",\n    monthly_requests      = 550_000,\n    total_tokens_per_req  = 6230,\n    cache_multiplier      = 0.975,\n    blended_cost_per_req  = 0.0351,\n    batch_fraction        = 0.05,\n    batch_discount        = 0.50,\n    provider_price_factor = 1.15,\n)\n\nfor s in [bear_scenario, base_scenario, bull_scenario]:\n    print(f\"{s.scenario_name}: ${s.annual_cost_usd:,.0f}/yr\")\n# Bear:  $X/yr (optimised platform, slow adoption)\n# Base:  $Y/yr (expected trajectory)\n# Bull:  $Z/yr (rapid growth, no optimisation)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sensitivity Analysis: Finding the Key Driver"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "After building the three scenarios, run a one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis to identify which driver contributes the most variance to the annual cost. This tells the FinOps team where to invest optimisation effort and which assumptions to validate most carefully with product owners."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def sensitivity_analysis(\n    base:     AnnualCostScenario,\n    bear:     AnnualCostScenario,\n    bull:     AnnualCostScenario,\n) -> dict[str, float]:\n    \"\"\"Return {driver: annual_cost_range_usd} for each driver.\"\"\"\n    drivers = {}\n\n    def swing(field: str) -> float:\n        low  = getattr(bear, field)\n        high = getattr(bull, field)\n        from dataclasses import replace\n        low_scenario  = replace(base, **{field: low})\n        high_scenario = replace(base, **{field: high})\n        return abs(high_scenario.annual_cost_usd - low_scenario.annual_cost_usd)\n\n    for field in [\n        \"monthly_requests\", \"cache_multiplier\", \"blended_cost_per_req\",\n        \"batch_fraction\", \"provider_price_factor\",\n    ]:\n        drivers[field] = swing(field)\n\n    return dict(sorted(drivers.items(), key=lambda x: -x[1]))\n\nswings = sensitivity_analysis(base_scenario, bear_scenario, bull_scenario)\nfor driver, range_usd in swings.items():\n    print(f\"{driver}: ${range_usd:,.0f} annual swing\")\n# Output ranks drivers by impact \u2014 focus optimisation on the top two"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Connecting Scenarios to Budget Reserves"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The output of scenario planning is not just a forecast \u2014 it is an input to the budget approval process. The standard approach: set the committed team budget to the base scenario, request a contingency reserve equal to 50% of the bull-minus-base gap, and flag that the reserve requires CFO sign-off to unlock. This prevents the bull scenario from silently consuming budget while preserving agility if growth outpaces the base forecast."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def budget_recommendation(\n    base_annual:       float,\n    bull_annual:       float,\n    contingency_pct:   float = 0.50,\n) -> dict:\n    contingency = (bull_annual - base_annual) * contingency_pct\n    return {\n        \"committed_budget\":     round(base_annual, -2),\n        \"contingency_reserve\":  round(contingency, -2),\n        \"total_ask\":            round(base_annual + contingency, -2),\n        \"unlock_trigger\":       \"Actual spend tracking to exceed base by >15% for 2 consecutive months\",\n    }"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summary"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scenario planning for token cost drivers converts a single-point forecast into a structured view of the cost space and its key uncertainties. The six primary drivers \u2014 request volume, tokens per request, cache hit rate, model tier, provider pricing, and batch fraction \u2014 each have independent bear / base / bull ranges. Sensitivity analysis identifies which two or three drivers dominate the annual cost variance and should receive the most validation effort."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "Model tier is typically the highest-leverage driver \u2014 a 10\u201320\u00d7 price difference between frontier and mini models means even a 10% shift in routing has material cost impact."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "Build scenarios bottom-up from driver assumptions, not top-down from a target number \u2014 top-down scenarios conceal which assumptions are doing the work."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "Run sensitivity analysis after building scenarios to rank drivers by annual swing \u2014 this tells you where to spend optimisation engineering time."
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  "Set the committed budget to the base scenario and request a contingency reserve for the bull gap \u2014 this prevents budget surprises without requiring worst-case budgeting."
                ]
              }
